commentBody:
@Deborah W no reason why it couldn’t cook in the IP. I’d suggest cutting back the water to 4.5c and cooking on high for 10-ish minutes with natural release. If it’s not the texture or consistency you want, keep experimenting until you get it right.

BTW, I regularly cook grits in the IP. 1c stone ground grits, 3.5c water, 10-12 min quick release. Sometimes they need to cook a bit longer (I live at high elevation), other times perfect.

Alt: porridge setting in the rice cooker. It takes about 2 hours in mine but again, I’m at high elevation so if you’re closer to see level, you may not need as much time or water as I do.

@SKG 
We bought a Whirly popcorn pot for made for induction, no pot movement involved, which I think would scratch the cooking surface. .. One turns a crank that stirs the popcorn inside the pot. Makes alot quickly. We make caramel corn around the holidays and the Whirly gets a workout.
We used to be electric, not induction, and was forced to get the Whirly stainless steel version if we wanted popcorn. Couldn't be happier.

@Mallard

That’s funny — I didn’t even notice that it was calling for boneless skinless until you mentioned it. I would probably do it with bone in and skin on thighs, too.

I suggest cooking the chicken all the way through before doing the rest of the recipe. Then you can just nestle a chicken back in to heat it back up.

@Boris I was thinking about this as well, (because my kids don't care for the texture of mushrooms).  
      I was thinking of adding some canned, drained chicken peas or cannellini beans; that'd also save time, as they required no slicing!
    I also am considering some slicing some  sun-dried tomatoes, the kind in a jar with olive oil, so they're already softened & ready to turn into jammy goodness on the sheet pan! Plus, SD tomatoes will help boost the umami-quotient. I imagine the SD tomatoes should probably be added in, say, the last 15 to 20 mins of cooking though, their high sugar content could cause them to burn.

@Shorty Attentionspan
I agree. Polenta is always a 4:1 ratio of water (broth, or milk, or a mixture of those liquids) & FINE cornmeal. Haven’t made this, but it sounds like cornmeal croutons. 
* try 1cup water, 1 cup broth, 2 cups milk. So creamy and tasty.

@Prof

Yes! 

There was a similar recipe a few months ago in the NYT. I made it, and it was quite tasty!

@Ray

I think your comments speak to the fact that the amount of fat in pork belly, although always a fatty cut, can vary. Perhaps the recipe could be amended to tell us approximately how much oil should be in the pan when we add the plums? 

But if you’re an experienced cook, it makes sense to consider how much oil you have in the pan before you add the plums. If it seems excessive, pour some off (but not down the drain!).
